"short_span_min_tokens": {"details": {"min_tokens": 2, "token_count": 230}, "passed": true}}, "text": "National Assembly Elections in South Vietnam\n\nAgainst a backdrop of official concern over spreading Communist insurgency in neighboring Laos, South Vietnam is preparing to hold National Assembly elections on 30 August. Elaborate government control measures and the absence of opposition parties assure that the 123 seats at stake will be filled predominantly by candidates espoused by the Diem regime. The majority of those elected will probably be members of the government's mass political party, the National Revolutionary Movement, and the remainder largely \"independents\" who comprise the bulk of the more than 400 candidates.\n\nThe government is anxious for the elections to appear as democratic as possible but apparently is prepared to take steps such as intimidation and marshalling of military votes to defeat candidates considered inimical to national interests. Included in this category are several candidates backed by the various labor unions in South Vietnam which do not enjoy the administration's full confidence and are suspected of Communist penetration. Next to considerations of political reliability, the government is interested in improving the quality of the unicameral legislature above the level of the initial National Assembly elected in March 1956.\n\nDespite stringent security measures, Communist-instigated acts of terrorism aimed at discrediting the Diem government are possible during the election period. The assassination of two American MAAG members last July highlights the increasing aggressiveness of the well-entrenched Communist underground in South Vietnam", "token_count": 230, "token_end_0based": 229, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "national assembly elections in south vietnam against a backdrop of official concern over spreading communist insurgency in neighboring laos south vietnam is preparing to hold national assembly elections 